# [[except|Except]], except for, not counting; were it not for.
#* {{RQ:Shakespeare Merchant of Venice|V|i|text=I once did lend my body for his wealth, <br> Which, '''but for''' him that had your husband's ring, <br> Had quite miscarried: {{...}}}}
#* {{RQ:Charlotte Bronte Jane Eyre|XXXVI|text=She had a woman to take care of her called Mrs Poole — an able woman in her line, and very trustworthy, '''but for''' one fault — a fault common to a deal of them nurses and matrons — ''she kept a bottle of gin by her'', and now and then took a drop over-much.}}
#* {{quote-text|en|year=1880|author={{w|Mark Twain}}|title=''{{w|A Tramp Abroad}}''|passage='''But for''' that beneficent drug, not one of those men would have slept a moment during that fearful night.}}
#* {{RQ:Stevenson Jekyll and Hyde|text=In the whole extent of the house, which '''but for''' the old woman remained otherwise empty, Mr. Hyde had only used a couple of rooms}}
#* {{quote-text|en|year=1992|author=Najīb Maḥfūẓ|title=''Sugar Street''|page=48|passage='''But for''' the stinging cold of January, this Casanova would not have taken shelter behind the coffeehouse window, {{...}}.}}
# [[despite]]; [[in spite of]]

====Usage notes====
* A clause that uses the preposition {{m|en||but for}} will frequently use the conditional mood (for example, by using the verb {{m|en|would}}), especially when the {{m|en||but for}} phrase appears at the beginning of its sentence.

